Random Matters: Correlations Vary¶

In [82]:
live = pd.read_csv("datasets/babysamp-98.txt", sep = "\t")

#Graph will look different for different samples
sns.scatterplot(data = live.sample(n = 50), x = "DadAge", y = "MomAge")
plt.show()
In [85]:
print(live.corr().iloc[0,1])

0.7516507040838809
In [89]:
#Sample 10000 times, each time samples 50 examples
corrs = np.zeros(10000)

for i in range(10000):
    sample = live.sample(n = 50)
    corrs[i] = sample.corr().iloc[0,1]
    
#Plot the sampling distribution
sns.histplot(data = corrs)
plt.xlabel("Correlation of Mother's Age and Father's Age in Samples of Size 50")
plt.ylabel("$ of Samples")
plt.show()

Section 6.4: Straightening Scatterplots¶

It’s often possible to straightend scatterplots through use of a transformation.

In [117]:
#Figure 6.10, page 189
fstops = pd.read_csv("datasets/f-stops.txt", sep = "\t")
fstops

sns.scatterplot(data = fstops, x = "ShutterSpeed", y = "F-stop")
plt.xlabel("Shutter Speed (sec)")
plt.ylabel("f/Stop")
plt.show()

print(fstops.corr())

                F-stop  ShutterSpeed
F-stop        1.000000      0.978672
ShutterSpeed  0.978672      1.000000

The Ladder of Powers¶

f/Stops Again¶

In [116]:
#Figure 6.11, page 191
sns.scatterplot(data = fstops, x = "ShutterSpeed", y = np.log(fstops["F-stop"]))
plt.xlabel("Shutter Speed (sec)")
plt.ylabel("Log(f/Stop)")
plt.show()
In [115]:
#Figure 6.12, page 191
sns.scatterplot(data = fstops, x = "ShutterSpeed", y = fstops["F-stop"] ** 2)
plt.xlabel("Shutter Speed (sec)")
plt.ylabel("f/Stop squared")
plt.show()

See the displays in “What Can Go Wrong?” on pages 192-193.
